sub_title: PhD candidate at IHS, Erasmus University Rotterdam. Researching Nature Based Solutions for Quito, Ecuador
summary:
Tannya Pico is an architect with more than 20 years of broad practice in architectural design, construction, and teaching. Graduated from the Pontifical Catholic University of Ecuador, she also holds a master's degree from the Polytechnic University of Catalunya. 

Tannya has working experience in the USA, Spain, and Ecuador, being involved in developing diverse and significant projects. Some of her remarkable positions are as the Architecture and Sustainability Master Program coordinator in PUCE, architecture field director at the Seymour Airport on the Galápagos Islands and in the New International Airport of Ecuador in Quito, and as a technical representative from UNDP for the design and construction of the New Common house of the United Nations of Ecuador. Currently, she is a Ph.D. candidate in IHS, and her investigation is about the absorptive capacities of Nature-Based Solutions in the Ecuadorian context.
